Bedding pattern terms

 

DisplayName

TextDescription

Tracking

Thickening upward cycles

Beds occur in packages in which the average thickness of individual beds increases up section to the top of the cycle interval.

SMR050404

Bed offlap

Individual beds in a vertical sequence lap progressively sideward as a result of depocenter migration, thereby leading to bed downlap (foreset accumulation).

MattiSetGlossary090903

Bed onlap

Individual beds in a vertical sequence lap progressively higher and laterally onto a surface formed on older underlying beds (buttress contact).

MattiSetGlossary090903

Bed downlap

Individual beds in a vertical sequence lap progressively downward and laterally onto a surface formed on older underlying beds (bottomset accumulation).

MattiSetGlossary090903

Thinning upward cycles

Beds occur in packages in which the average thickness of individual beds decreases up section to the top of the cycle interval.

SMR050404

 

 

Bedding Style terms

DisplayName

TextDescription

Tracking

Amalgamated bedding

Beds occur in stacks of beds having similar composition and texture, but separated by abrupt discontinuities that are erosional.

MattiSedGlossary090903; Campbell, 1967 and Collinson and Thompson, 1989

Non parallel bedded

Bed sole and upper surface converge over distances of a few tens of meters to a few hundreds of meters.

MattiSetGlossary090903

Non parallel bedded wavy

 

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Non parallel bedded wavy discontinuous

 

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Non parallel bedded wavy continuous

 

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Non parallel bedded curved

 

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Non parallel bedded curved discontinuous

Outcrop-scale fabric defined by non-parallel, curviplanar bedding surfaces that have lateral extents averaging less than 10 m. Curved bedding surfaces are either concave or convex over their exposed extent; if they were concave and convex across the exposed extent, the bedding would be wavy.

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Non parallel bedded curved continuous

 

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Non parallel bedded planar

 

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Non parallel bedded planar continuous

 

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Non parallel bedded planar discontinuous

 

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Fissil bedding

Bedding parting surfaces separated by < 2mm (on average) over exposed outcrop (base on Jackson, 1997).

SMR

Channelate bedding

Bed sole forms an erosional channel into underlying beds.

MattiSetGlossary090903

Parallel bedded

Bed sole and upper surface are parallel for many tens to hundreds of meters.

Bedding thickness terms

DisplayName

TextDescription

Tracking

Sedimentary bedding layer thickness

Terms for average thickness of bedding layers (individual sedimentation units) within a geologic unit.

mattiSedPickList3-051603; SMR050304

medium bedded

Sedimentation units (strata) average 10-30 cm thick.

mattiSedPickList3-051603; (modified from Ingram, 1954; see Campbell, 1967 and Collinson and Thompson, 1989)

non bedded

No apparent stratificaton in geologic unit.

mattiSedPickList3-051603; (modified from Ingram, 1954; see Campbell, 1967 and Collinson and Thompson, 1989)

thin bedded

Sedimentation units (strata) average 3-10 cm thick.

mattiSedPickList3-051603; (modified from Ingram, 1954; see Campbell, 1967 and Collinson and Thompson, 1989)

very thin bedded

Sedimentation units (strata) average 1-3 cm thick.

mattiSedPickList3-051603; (modified from Ingram, 1954; see Campbell, 1967 and Collinson and Thompson, 1989)

laminated

Sedimentation units (strata) average < 1 cm thick in geologic unit..

mattiSedPickList3-051603; (modified from Ingram, 1954; see Campbell, 1967 and Collinson and Thompson, 1989)

very thick bedded

Sedimentation units (strata) average >100 cm thick.

mattiSedPickList3-051603; (modified from Ingram, 1954; see Campbell, 1967 and Collinson and Thompson, 1989)

thick bedded

Sedimentation units (strata) average 30-100 cm thick.

mattiSedPickList3-051603; (modified from Ingram, 1954; see Campbell, 1967 and Collinson and Thompson, 1989)

sedimentary bedding parting thickness

Terminology to describe the average thickness of rock between bedding parting surfaces in a sedimentary rock. Parting surfaces commonly coincide with bed boundaries and contribute to the recognition of stratification.

mattiSedPickList3-051603; (modified from Ingram, 1954; see Campbell, 1967 and Collinson and Thompson, 1989)

Fissile parting

Parting surfaces spaced 1- 3 mm on average.

mattiSedPickList3-051603; (modified from Ingram, 1954; see Campbell, 1967 and Collinson and Thompson, 1989)

Platy parting

Parting surfaces spaced 3-10 mm on average.

mattiSedPickList3-051603; (modified from Ingram, 1954; see Campbell, 1967 and Collinson and Thompson, 1989)

Massive parting

Parting surfaces spaced >100 cm on average.

mattiSedPickList3-051603; (modified from Ingram, 1954; see Campbell, 1967 and Collinson and Thompson, 1989)

Flaggy parting

Parting surfaces spaced 1-3 cm on average.

mattiSedPickList3-051603; (modified from Ingram, 1954; see Campbell, 1967 and Collinson and Thompson, 1989)

Blocky bedding parting

Bedding parting surfaces spaced 10-30 cm on average.

mattiSedPickList3-051603; (modified from Ingram, 1954; see Campbell, 1967 and Collinson and Thompson, 1989)

Papery parting

Parting surfaces spaced <1 mm on average.

mattiSedPickList3-051603; (modified from Ingram, 1954; see Campbell, 1967 and Collinson and Thompson, 1989)

Slabby parting

Parting surfaces spaced 3-10 cm on average.

mattiSedPickList3-051603; (modified from Ingram, 1954; see Campbell, 1967 and Collinson and Thompson, 1989)

Consolidation degree terms

DisplayName

TextDescription

Tracking

Consolidated

Particulate constituents of a compound material adhere to each other strongly enough that the aggregate can be considered a solid material in its own right..

SMR101703

Consolidation degree terms

Vocabulary for specifying degree of consolidatioin of an Earth material.

SMR Vocabulary organization terms

Consolidation not specified

In normative descriptions, indicates that consolidation state is not a determining factor in identification.

no tracking record assigned

consolidation state unknown

No data to determine consoliation state.

no tracking record assigned

Indurated

Requires blasting or heavy equipment to loosen; Relative density 0.9-1.0 (NADMSLTTs 2004 after Bowles, 1984). Synonomous with lithified. Rings to blow of hammer..

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Loosely consolidated

Easily shoveled, can be indented with fingers; Relative density 0.2-0.4 (NADMSLTTs 2004, after Bowles, 1984, slightly modified by SMR).

SLTTsBowles

Moderately consolidated

Shoveled with difficulty (NADMSLTTs 2004, after Bowles, 1984).

SLTTsBowles

moderately indurated

Multiple blows with standard rock hammer (< 1kg) are required to break rock..

mattiSedPickList3-051603; SMR050304

slightly indurated

Rock can be broken with single blow from standard rock hammer (< 1 kg mass).

mattiSedPickList3-051603; SMR050304

Unconsolidated

Particulate constituents of a compound material do not adhere to each other strongly enough that the aggregate can be considered a solid in its own right..

SMR101703

Variable induration

Material is lithified, but induration varies at scale of description.

SMR

Very Loosely consolidated

Easily indented with fingers; Relative density 0.0-0.2 (NADMSLTTs 2004 after Bowles, 1984).

no tracking record assigned

Well consolidated

Requires pick to loosen for shoveling; relative density 0.7-0.9 (NADMSLTTs 2004 after Bowles, 1984).

SLTTsBowles

well indurated

Particles in the rock are strongly bound together such that rock surface can only be broken with great difficulty using standard rock hammer (< 1kg mass)..

mattiSedPickList3-051603; SMR050304

Earth material composition terms

Same as geologic unit composition terms, but without chemical classification terms included in that vocabulary

DisplayName

TextDescription

Tracking

Quartz-feldspar-pelitic

Rock for which the sum of modal quartz+feldspar+ mica + aluminous mineral is >=70%.

SMR, SLTTM1.0

Semi-pelitic

Rock for which the sum of modal quartz+feldspar+ mica + aluminous mineral is >=70%, and quartz+ feldspar < 60%..

SMR, SLTTM1.0

Calcareous-semi-pelitic

Rock for which the sum of modal quartz+feldspar+ mica + aluminous mineral is >=70%, and quartz+ feldspar < 60% and carbonate + calcsilicate minerals > 10%.

SMR, SLTTM1.0

Quartzo-feldspathic

Rock for which the sum of modal quartz+feldspar+ mica + aluminous mineral is >=70%, and quartz + feldspar (sensu Robertson, 1999) >60%..

SMR, SLTTM1.0

Calcareous quartzo-feldspathic

Rock consists of 10%-50% carbonate or calcsilicate minerals, and micaceous or aluminous minerals form <40% of non-(carbonate or calcsilicate) minerals and quartz forms <60% of the non-carbonate + calcsilicate minerals.

SMR, SLTTM1.0

Quartzose

Material consists of >=75% quartz.

SMR, SLTTM1.0

Calcareous-quartzose

Rock consists of 10%-50% carbonate or calcsilicate minerals, and micaceous or aluminous minerals form <40% of non-(carbonate or calcsilicate) minerals, and quartz forms >=75% of the non-(carbonate + calcsilicate) minerals.

SMR, SLTTM1.0

Pelitic

Rock for which the sum of modal quartz+feldspar+ mica + aluminous mineral is >=70%, and aluminous mineral + mica content is >=40%..

SMR, SLTTM1.0

Calcareous-pelitic

Rock consists of 10%-50% carbonate or calcsilicate minerals, and micaceous or aluminous minerals form >=40% of non-(carbonate or calcsilicate) minerals.

SMR, SLTTM1.0

Greisen

Hydrothermal rock consisting of >70% quartz + muscovite or lepodilite, with accessory (>1%) topaz or tourmaline (or other flourine-bearing phase). In a hierarchy based purely on description, would be a kind of semi-pelitic rock (10-40% aluminous minerals; <60% quartz+feldspar) or quartz-feldspathic (<40% aluminous and >60% quartz + feldspar).

SMR, SLTTM1.0

Mono mineralic

TextDescription

Clast supported fabric

A depositional fabric in which the sand- and gravel-size particles touch at point contacts and form a supporting framework, with any fine matrix merely occupying the interstices between the coarser grains.

MattiSetGlossary1.0 060103

Fabric defined by long axis of tabular clasts stacked like shingles to define a surface that makes a small angle with the bedding surface.

SMR092603

Matrix supported fabric

A depositional fabric in which finer-grained clastic particles support the sediment mass while coarser-grained particles-float in the matrix with minimal point contacts between them. The result is a distinctive bimodal or multi-modal grain-size distribution.

massive sedimentary fabric

The depositional fabric of a sedimentation unit is structureless-i.e., the fabric lacks any form of geometry or particle organization such as lamination, cross lamination, and size grading. Massive does not refer to the character or thickness of bedding.

Fabric characterized by mosaic of equidimensional, anhedral grains; inequant grains, if present, are randomly oriented; grain boundaries apporach bubble-like configuration (crystalloblastic), with dihedral angles between faces commonly near 120 degrees.

Foliation

A penetrative planar fabric in a rock..

SMR

Foliation crystalloblastic

Foliation in a metamorphic rock with a granoblastic texture. Fabric elements may be layering or aligned tabular crystals or crystal aggregates..

SMR

Schistosity

Planar foliation defined by aligned planar or tabular mineral grains, in which the shape of the grains is related to the crystal habit of the mineral, not deformation of grain shape..

SMR

laminated differentiated foliation

Foliation defined by compositional segregation, in which the layers are less than 1 cm thick..

SMR

Foliation compositional layering

Layering defined by mineralogical variations in a rock body, commonly associated with layers that have sharp boundaries. Also known as gneissic foliation.

SMR

Foliation compositional layering mineral segregation

Layering defined by mineralogical variations in a rock body, commonly associated with layers that have sharp boundaries. Origin of compositional variations interpreted to be result of solid-state reactions in rock body (metamorphic segregation)..

SMR

Foliation vague compositional layering

Compositional layering and of uncertain origin.. formed by subtle mineralogical or textural variations, with gradational layer boundaries

SMR_DI25DatabaseDevelopment

Foliation compositional layering migmatitic

Layering defined by mineralogical variations in a rock body, commonly associated with layers that have sharp boundaries. Compositional variations are result of melt segregation during high-grade metamorphism; some layers have magmatic/igneous mineralogy.

SMR

Foliation compositional layering inherited from protolith

Layering defined by mineralogical variations in a rock body, commonly associated with layers that have sharp boundaries. Layering is relict of compositional variations in protolith, typically heterogeneous sedimentary or volcanic rock..

SMR

Foliation nebulitic

Vague layering defined by subtle compositional and textural variations. The descriptor nebulitic is from migmatite terminology, and the term fabric is associated with high-grade metamorphic rocks intermediate between igneous and metamorphic. Distinction from textural and compositional layering varieties is not clearly defined ..

SMR

Mylonitic foliation generic

Generic mylonitic shape fabric; defined by shape of deformed mineral grains or aggregates of mineral grains; greater than 10% TRIG matrix.

SMR

Mylonitic foliation ultramylonite

Ultramylonitic foliation; greater than 90% of rock is matrix due to tectonic grain size reduction processes.

SMR

Mylonitic foliation protomylonite

Protomylonitic foliation; 10-50% of rock is matrix due to tectonic grain size reduction processes.

SMR

Mylonitic foliation weak grain shape fabric

Foliation defined by shape of deformed, originally equant grains, in which aspect ratio of deformed grains is generally less than 3 to 1 (longest to shortest axis).

SMR

Mylonitic foliation well developed s tectonite foliation

Foliation defined by aligned tectonically flattened mineral grains, and planar or tabular grains rotated to parallel foliation, as well as cleavage along slip or shear surfaces. Intermediate fabric in mylonite series..

SMRDI21DataSetSetup

Mylonitic foliation mylonite

Mylonitic foliation; 50-90% of rock is matrix due to tectonic grain size reduction processes.

SMR

weak shape fabric

Planar foliation defined by aligned mineral grains, in cases where less than 50% of rock consists of mineral grains defining the foliation. Shape of mineral grains due to crystal habit, deformation, some combination of these or not specified..

SMR

Weak schistosity

Planar foliation defined by aligned mineral grains whose crystal habit imparts the tabular shape defining the foliation, in cases where less than 50% of rock consists of mineral grains defining the foliation..

SMR_DI25DatabaseDevelopment

Cleavage

A planar tectonic foliation in a rock characterized by a tendency for the rock to break parallel to the foliation..

SMR

Cleavage slaty

Continuous planar foliation defined by aligned fine to very-fine grained phylosilicate mineral grains. Grades into schistosity as grain size increases. [synonomous with fissility].

SMR

Cleavage generic crenulation

Superclass for a cleavage that is overprinted on an older foliation.

SMRDataBaseDevelopment

Cleavage spaced crenulation

A crenulation cleavage in which the cleavage domains have discrete boundaries.

SMRDataBaseDevelopment

Cleavage continuous crenulation

Cleavage defined by long, thin limbs of crenulation folds of pre-existing foliation, in which the boundaries between cleavage domains and lithons are gradational. Both the crenulation foliation and the crenulated foliation are easily visible. Grades to spaced crenulation cleavage as boundaries of cleavage domains become sharp, and transposed foliations as crenulation foliation obscures the crenulated foliation..

SMR

Cleavage close disjunct

Spaced cleavage in sandstone or phyllosilicate-poor rock, defined by partings of uncertain origin, and does not crenulate an existing cleavage. (sometimes called 'fracture cleavage'). Cleavage domains have no apparent thickness, and are spaced less than 5 cm on average. Domainal if cleavage is clearly developed in some parts of outcrop but not in others..

SMR

Cleavage spaced disjunct close joints

Cleavage typically in phyllosilicate-poor rock, in which the cleavage domains have no apparent thickness, and are spaced between 5 cm and 25 cm, and do not crenulate an older foliation. Cleavage domains are regularly spaced, and penetrative on a 1-10 m scale..

SMR

Foliation generic composite

SMR

SMR

Mylonite with continuous compositional layering greater than 5 mm thick. Continuous means individual layers can be traced more than 1 m.

Layering interpreted to have originated as sedimentary bedding that has been transposed as a result of metamorphism and deformation.

Joints

Parting surfaces in rock that occur in crudely parallel orientation, spaced >25 cm on average if in a very regular joint set. Spacing is more variable and alignment of surfaces is cruder that cleavage..

SMR

Lineation crenulation

Lineation defined by small-scale wrinkles, typically of phylosillicate minerals, on another surface, typically a cleavage or schistosity. Use instead of intersection lineation if the wrinkles are the measured feature and the intersecting planar feature is not apparent.

Interstices between plagioclase crystals forming framework of an igneous rock are filled with glass, cryptocrystalline material, or non-granular deuteric or secondary minerals, such as serpentine, nontronite, chlorite, calcite, zeolite or sodalite..

Lathes of plagioclase in a matrix of coarse subhedral pyroxene such that the feldspar laths appear to be largelo or entirely cnclosed in pyroxene. Length of plagioclase laths is less than diameter of pyroxene grains..

Abundant, closely spaced, minute, angular cavities between laths of feldspar of random orientation; cavities bear no definitie relation th ethe arrangement of enclosing feldspar. Feldspar bordering cavities are of same size and composition as in the areas between the cavities.

Minute worm-like or finger like bodies of quartz enclosed in sodic plagioclase.

SMR_WilliamsTurnerGilbert1954

Laths of plagioclase in a matrix of coarse subhedral pyroxene such that the feldspar laths appear to be largely enclosed in pyroxene. Length of plagioclase laths is greater than diameter of pyroxene grains..

Framework of feldspar crystals contains ferromagnesian mineral grains in angular interstices between crystals.

SMR_WilliamsTurnerGilbert1954

Lathes of plagioclase in a matrix of glass such that the feldspar laths appear to be largely or entirely enclosed in glass.

SMR

Sedimentary Structure

A structure in sedimentary material formed at any point of its life cycle before it becomes a rock. A sedimentary structure can be one of the following:
(1) structures that intrinsically reflect the conditions of sediment deposition (e.g., transportation and deposition of sediment);
(2) structures formed during penecontemporaneous modification of sediment shortly after its accumulation, and intrinsically reflecting depositional conditions (e.g., downslope slumping, biologic activity);
(3) structures representing modification of sediment while it is soft and weak, but not intrinsically related to depositional conditions (e.g., dewatering, loading);
(4) structures formed during diagenesis and lithification (e.g., concretionary nodules, dissolution voids)..

SLTTs

Secondary sedimentary structure

A sedimentary structure "...that originated subsequently to the deposition...of the rock in which it is found...; esp. an epigenetic sedimentary structure, such as a concretion or nodule produced by chemical action, or a sedimentary dike formed by infilling- Glossary of Geology (Jackson, 1997, p. 576). Includes deformation structures, dissolution structures, hardground structures, and epigenetic-growth structures.

MattiSetGlossary1.0 060103

silcrete soil horizon

Silcretes are very hard layers of silica-enriched materials formed beneath the surface in soils, unconsolidated sediments, and permeable rocks. These materials range from silica-cemented sand and gravel to an amorphous matrix enriched with small silica particles. There is little agreement as to their classification and origin. A minimum silica (SiO2) content of 85 percent by weight has been proposed by Summerfield (1983a [1]) to distinguish silcretes from other duricrusts. Although not restricted to arid regions, silcrete zones are found in many deserts, and they are most extensive and prominent topographic features in Australian deserts. Silcrete tends to form roughly horizontal, highly resistant layers generally less than 5 m thick. When exposed by erosion, silcrete forms highly resistant cap rocks of scarps ("breakaways" in Australia). These cap rocks resemble quartzite. Many talus slopes and gravel plains in areas of exposed silcrete consist of silcrete fragments eroded from the cap rock. Buried silcrete layers thicker than 3 m are rare, and they are generally not laterally continuous over large areas. In the Kalahari Desert of southern Africa, they occur widely as layers within sandy surface deposits, and they are also found along old, dry river courses such as the Molopo River (Summerfield, 1983b [2]). These buried silcrete layers can be virtually impenetrable..

mattiSedPickList3-051603; http://www.tec.army.mil/research/products/desert_guide/lsmsheet/lssilc.htm

The calcium carbonate is -...precipitated from solution and re-deposited through the agency of infiltrating waters, or deposited by the escape of carbon dioxide from vadose water- (modified from the Glossary of Geology, Jackson, 1997, p. 91). Although the Glossary of Geology indicates a pedogenic origin for calcrete, SLTTS_1.0 uses the term only to indicate a secondary feature, without specifying an origin.

A type of sedimentary hardground consisting of "a limestone which has been cemented on the seafloor. The hardground surface may be encrusted, discolored, case-hardened, bored, and solution-ridden. It implies a gap in sedimentation and may be preserved stratigraphically as an unconformity" Glossary of Geology, (Jackson, 1997, p. 290).

MattiSetGlossary1.0 060103

Beachrock

"A type of sedimentary hardground consisting of -a friable to well-cemented sedimentary rock, formed in the intertidal zone in a tropical or subtropical region, consisting of sand or gravel (detrital and/or skeletal) cemented with calcium carbonate" Glossary of Geology, (Jackson, 1997, p. 59).

Penecontemporaneous sedimentary structure

An inorganic structure formed shortly after the deposition of sediment, usually involving deformation (shape change) or disruption of the sediment mass, and intrinsically related to depositional conditions.

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Salt crystal Imprint

A penecontemporaneous sedimentary structure consisting of an imprint formed by solution of a soluble salt crystal (derived from Glossary of Geology definition of salt-crystal cast; Jackson, 1997, p. 563). Can sometimes form casts on the lower surfaces of beds.

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Desiccation Mudcrack

"A penecontemporaneous sedimentary structure consisting of an irregular fracture in a crudely polygonal pattern, formed by the shrinkage of clay, silt, or mud, generally in the course of drying under the influence of atmospheric conditions" Glossary of Geology, (Jackson, 1997, p. 422).

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Icewedge Casts and Polygons

 

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Icewedge polygon

A penecontemporaneous sedimentary structure consisting of "a large nonsorted polygon characterized by borders of intersecting ice wedges, found only in permafrost regions and formed by contraction of frozen ground. The fissured borders delineating the polygon may be ridges...or shallow troughs....In plan the pattern tends to be three- to six-sided" Glossary of Geology (Jackson, 1997, p. 317).

MattiSetGlossary1.0 060103

Ice wedge cast

A penecontemporaneous sedimentary structure consisting of a "sedimentary structure formed by the filing of the space formerly occupied by an ice wedge that had melted" Glossary of Geology (Jackson, 1997, p. 317).

MattiSetGlossary1.0 060103

Raindrop Impression

"A penecontemporaneous sedimentary structure synonymous with rain print--A small, shallow crater-like print surrounded by a slightly raised rim, formed in soft, fine sand, silt, or clay...by the impact of a falling raindrop, and sometimes preserved on the bedding planes of sedimentary rocks or as casts on the underside of...beds" Glossary of Geology, (Jackson, 1997, p. 530).

Fenestral Structures

 

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Olistostrome

A sedimentary deposit consisting of a chaotic mass of intimately mixed heterogeneous materials (such as blocks and muds) that accumulated by submarine gravity sliding or slumping of unconsolidated sediment- Glossary of Geology, (Jackson, 1997, p. 445)..

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Deformed Cross Stratification

A penecontemporaneous sedimentary structure consisting of oversteepened or overturned foresets that occur "...within single sets. The deformation ranges from foresets that dip more steeply than the angle of rest in the upper parts of sets (oversteepened) to extensive overturning of foresets into recumbent folds. The overfolding is always in the direction of the original foreset dip....[Oversteepening and overturning develop in response to] a shear force acting on the upper surface of a bedform, and in the same direction of the current that produced the bedform...." (Collinson and Thompson, 1989, p. 153-154)..

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Synsedimentary Fault

A penecontemporaneous sedimentary structure consisting of a surface or narrow zone of discrete slip separating blocks of internally coherent sediment, with displacement ranging from centimeters to hundreds of meters (Collinson and Thompson, 1989, p. 157). Also see Growth fault.

MattiSetGlossary1.0 060103

Slump Fold

"A penecontemporaneous sedimentary structure consisting of -an intraformational fold produced by slumping of soft sediments" Glossary of Geology, (Jackson, 1997, p. 530). Slumping is a response to local depositional-slope conditions.

MattiSetGlossary1.0 060103

Slump Scar

A penecontemporaneous sedimentary structure consisting of a pull-away scarp from which a submarine slump has detached and across which younger sediment is draped (Collinson and Thompson, 1989, p.158)..

MattiSetGlossary1.0 060103

Slump Block

"A penecontemporaneous sedimentary structure consisting of "the mass of material torn away as a coherent unit during slumping" Glossary of Geology, (Jackson, 1997, p. 600).

An inorganic sedimentary structure formed during the genesis of sedimentation units and sedimentary bedforms or caused by the scouring action of fluids, and intrinsically reflecting conditions of the sedimentary environment..

Primary Sedimentary Fabric

 

SMR 062803

Clast supported fabric

A depositional fabric in which the sand- and gravel-size particles touch at point contacts and form a supporting framework, with any fine matrix merely occupying the interstices between the coarser grains.

MattiSetGlossary1.0 060103

Imbricated Clast fabric

Fabric defined by long axis of tabular clasts stacked like shingles to define a surface that makes a small angle with the bedding surface.

SMR092603

Matrix supported fabric

A depositional fabric in which finer-grained clastic particles support the sediment mass while coarser-grained particles-float in the matrix with minimal point contacts between them. The result is a distinctive bimodal or multi-modal grain-size distribution.

mattiSedPickList3-051603

massive sedimentary fabric

The depositional fabric of a sedimentation unit is structureless-i.e., the fabric lacks any form of geometry or particle organization such as lamination, cross lamination, and size grading. Massive does not refer to the character or thickness of bedding.

mattiSedPickList3-051603

lamination

A type of syngenetic depositional structure (internal) where the depositional fabric has discrete to diffuse planar structure created by layers and (or) grains that are oriented parallel to bedding planes.

mattiSedPickList3-051603

planar lamination

A type of syngenetic depositional structure (internal) where the depositional fabric has discrete to diffuse planar structure created by lamina that are oriented parallel to bedding planes. Lamina are "The thinnest recognizable unit layer of original deposition in a sediment or sedimentary rock...; specif. such a sedimentary layer less than 1 cm in thickness (Otto, 1938, p. 575)" Glossary of Geology (Jackson, 1997, p. 355). Also see Campbell (1967, p. 16-20). "A lamina can be regarded as the smallest megascopic layer in a sedimentary sequence....[It] is relatively uniform in composition...[and] is generally not megascopic internally layered." (Reineck and Singh, 1980, p. 96).

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Bedding

Outcrop-scale fabric defined by layering that results from the successive stacking of sedimentation units, each of which generally formed under uniform depositional conditions (see discussions by Otto, 1938; McKee and Weir, 1953; Campbell, 1967; Reineck and Singh, 1980; Collinson and Thompson, 1989). Has properties of parallel or non-parallel surfaces; planar, curviplanar, or wavy surfaces; discontinuous or continous surfaces, clarity of development (crude, well-defined). Subtype terms identify commonly used combinations of properties.

MattiSedPickList082903

Erosional channel structure

A syngenetic erosional structure consisting of a trough-shaped depression scoured downward into older earth materials by streamflows, wave action, storm surges, density currents, etc.; range from decimeters to many hundreds of meters in scale. Where appropriate, erosion channels can be classified either as (1) penecontemporaneous channels scoured into previously deposited material or (2) channels scoured into older material along a hardground that may mark an unconformity.

Sedimentary structures resulting from the erosion of sediment by moving water.

mattiSedPickList3-051603; SMR050304

Swash marks

A type of syngenetic erosional structure consisting of "A thin delicate wavy or arcuate line or very small ridge on a beach, marking the farthest advance of a wave uprush. It is convex landward, and consists of fine sand...." Glossary of Geology, (Jackson, 1997, p. 643).

MattiSetGlossary1.0 060103

Rill marks

A type of syngenetic erosional structure consisting of "A small, dendritic channel, groove, or furrow formed on the surface of beach mud or sand by a wave-generated rill or by a retreating tide" Glossary of Geology, (Jackson, 1997, p. 550).

MattiSetGlossary1.0 060103

Scour marks

A syngenetic erosional sedimentary structure. "A current mark produced by the cutting or scouring action of a current of water flowing over the bottom" Glossary of Geology (Jackson, 1997, p. 574).

MattiSetGlossary1.0 060103

Obstacle Scour Current Crescent

-...a scour mark produced by the interaction of an obstacle on the bed and a current flowing around it- Glossary of Geology, (Jackson, 1997, p. 442). The mark typically consists of crescent or horseshoe shaped ridges around an object on the base of a bed.

MattiSetGlossary1.0 060103

transverse scours

"A scour mark whose long axis is transverse to the main direction of the current" Glossary of Geology, (Jackson, 1997, p. 676). Transverse scours are small features that are morphologically transitional with flutes (Reineck and Singh, 1980, p. 74).

MattiSetGlossary1.0 060103

flute marks

A type of scour mark consisting of an elongate depression scoured in cohesive sediment by random eddy scour or by current eddies produced behind an obstacle. The marks range in length from a few cm to as much as 50 cm. They are elongate parallel to current flow, have a bulbous depression at the upstream end, and shallow and flare out downcurrent. Usually expressed as casts on the base of sand beds (Collinson and Thompson, 1989; Boggs, 2001).

mattiSedPickList3-051603

Gutter cast

A type of scour mark consisting of "A down-bulge on the bottom of a sedimentary bed, of great length (usually one meter or more) compared with its width and depth (a few centimeters to several decimeters)" Glossary of Geology, (Jackson, 1997, p. 287). According to Collinson and Thompson (1989, p. 43) they are U or V shaped isolated elongate ridges that project downward into underlying finer grained sediment from an otherwise flat bedding plane in vertical profile.

Regularly spaced ridges are separated by furrows a few millimeters to several centimeters apart. Ridges make the continuous structure" (Reineck and Singh, 1980, p. 75).

"A general descriptive term applied to a directional structure or to a small, wave like, mainly convex irregularity or penetration found on the underside of a bed of sandstone or siltstone along its contact with a finer-grained layer....The term usually refers to a filling of a primary sedimentary structure, e.g., a crack, track, groove. or other depression, formed on the surface of the underlying mud by such agents as currents, organisms, and unequal loading, and preserved as a sole cast after the underlying material has consolidated and weathered away...."Glossary of Geology (Jackson, 1997, p. 605).

granoblastic fabric

Fabric characterized by mosaic of equidimensional, anhedral grains; inequant grains, if present, are randomly oriented; grain boundaries apporach bubble-like configuration (crystalloblastic), with dihedral angles between faces commonly near 120 degrees.

SMR, base on Best, 1982

Poikiliblastic texture

Metamorphic fabric in which large crystals of one phase contain numerous small crystals of other phases. [NGMDB note: This is a fabric because it is defined based on the relationships between particles.].

based on Bates & Jackson, 1997

Planar penetrative tectonic structure

Foliation. Planar structure in a rock body defined by physical components that is related to deformation subsequent to solidification of the rock. Planar is used in the sense that the surface can be thought of as a plane in some sufficiently small neighborhood of any particular point on the surface. Penetrative denotes that the fabric elements defining the structure are repeated at distances so small, compared with the scale of the wholethat they can be considered to pervade it uniformly and be present at every point (paraphrase of Turner and Weiss, 1963, p. 21).

SMR

Foliation

A penetrative planar fabric in a rock..

SMR

Foliation crystalloblastic

Foliation in a metamorphic rock with a granoblastic texture. Fabric elements may be layering or aligned tabular crystals or crystal aggregates..

SMR

Schistosity

Planar foliation defined by aligned planar or tabular mineral grains, in which the shape of the grains is related to the crystal habit of the mineral, not deformation of grain shape..

SMR

laminated differentiated foliation

Foliation defined by compositional segregation, in which the layers are less than 1 cm thick..

SMR

Foliation compositional layering

Layering defined by mineralogical variations in a rock body, commonly associated with layers that have sharp boundaries. Also known as gneissic foliation.

SMR

Foliation compositional layering mineral segregation

Layering defined by mineralogical variations in a rock body, commonly associated with layers that have sharp boundaries. Origin of compositional variations interpreted to be result of solid-state reactions in rock body (metamorphic segregation)..

SMR

Foliation vague compositional layering

Compositional layering and of uncertain origin.. formed by subtle mineralogical or textural variations, with gradational layer boundaries

SMR_DI25DatabaseDevelopment

Foliation compositional layering migmatitic

Layering defined by mineralogical variations in a rock body, commonly associated with layers that have sharp boundaries. Compositional variations are result of melt segregation during high-grade metamorphism; some layers have magmatic/igneous mineralogy.

SMR

Foliation compositional layering inherited from protolith

Layering defined by mineralogical variations in a rock body, commonly associated with layers that have sharp boundaries. Layering is relict of compositional variations in protolith, typically heterogeneous sedimentary or volcanic rock..

SMR

Foliation nebulitic

Vague layering defined by subtle compositional and textural variations. The descriptor nebulitic is from migmatite terminology, and the term fabric is associated with high-grade metamorphic rocks intermediate between igneous and metamorphic. Distinction from textural and compositional layering varieties is not clearly defined ..

SMR

Mylonitic foliation generic

Generic mylonitic shape fabric; defined by shape of deformed mineral grains or aggregates of mineral grains; greater than 10% TRIG matrix.

SMR

Mylonitic foliation ultramylonite

Ultramylonitic foliation; greater than 90% of rock is matrix due to tectonic grain size reduction processes.

SMR

Mylonitic foliation protomylonite

Protomylonitic foliation; 10-50% of rock is matrix due to tectonic grain size reduction processes.

SMR

Mylonitic foliation weak grain shape fabric

Foliation defined by shape of deformed, originally equant grains, in which aspect ratio of deformed grains is generally less than 3 to 1 (longest to shortest axis).

SMR

Mylonitic foliation well developed s tectonite foliation

Foliation defined by aligned tectonically flattened mineral grains, and planar or tabular grains rotated to parallel foliation, as well as cleavage along slip or shear surfaces. Intermediate fabric in mylonite series..

SMRDI21DataSetSetup

Mylonitic foliation mylonite

Mylonitic foliation; 50-90% of rock is matrix due to tectonic grain size reduction processes.

SMR

weak shape fabric

Planar foliation defined by aligned mineral grains, in cases where less than 50% of rock consists of mineral grains defining the foliation. Shape of mineral grains due to crystal habit, deformation, some combination of these or not specified..

SMR

Weak schistosity

Planar foliation defined by aligned mineral grains whose crystal habit imparts the tabular shape defining the foliation, in cases where less than 50% of rock consists of mineral grains defining the foliation..

SMR_DI25DatabaseDevelopment

Cleavage

A planar tectonic foliation in a rock characterized by a tendency for the rock to break parallel to the foliation..

SMR

Cleavage slaty

Continuous planar foliation defined by aligned fine to very-fine grained phylosilicate mineral grains. Grades into schistosity as grain size increases. [synonomous with fissility].

SMR

Cleavage generic crenulation

Superclass for a cleavage that is overprinted on an older foliation.

SMRDataBaseDevelopment

Cleavage spaced crenulation

A crenulation cleavage in which the cleavage domains have discrete boundaries.

SMRDataBaseDevelopment

Cleavage continuous crenulation

Cleavage defined by long, thin limbs of crenulation folds of pre-existing foliation, in which the boundaries between cleavage domains and lithons are gradational. Both the crenulation foliation and the crenulated foliation are easily visible. Grades to spaced crenulation cleavage as boundaries of cleavage domains become sharp, and transposed foliations as crenulation foliation obscures the crenulated foliation..

Spaced cleavage in sandstone or phyllosilicate-poor rock, defined by partings of uncertain origin, and does not crenulate an existing cleavage. (sometimes called 'fracture cleavage'). Cleavage domains have no apparent thickness, and are spaced less than 5 cm on average. Domainal if cleavage is clearly developed in some parts of outcrop but not in others..

SMR

Cleavage spaced disjunct close joints

Cleavage typically in phyllosilicate-poor rock, in which the cleavage domains have no apparent thickness, and are spaced between 5 cm and 25 cm, and do not crenulate an older foliation. Cleavage domains are regularly spaced, and penetrative on a 1-10 m scale..

Linear penetrative tectonic structure

Lineation. Penetrative linear structure in a rock body defined by fabric elements that are defined by physical components that are the product of tectonic processes. Linear is used in the sense that the orientation of the structure can be represented as a line in some sufficiently small neighborhood of any point in the material containig the fabric. Penetrative denotes that the fabric elements defining the structure are repeated at distances so small, compared with the scale of the wholethat they can be considered to pervade it uniformly and be present at every point (paraphrase of Turner and Weiss, 1963, p. 21).

DisplayName

TextDescription

Tracking

Not metamorphosed

Rock or sediment not metamorphosed.

SMR 081303

Metamorphosed grade not specified

Rock is metamorphosed, may have any value for metamorphic grade.

SMR 081303

very low metamorphic grade

Rock very slightly metamorphosed, protolith structure ubiquitous; mineral assemblage of zeolite facies, subgreenschist facies, or low temperature part of blueschist facies. Mineral assemblages according to Fry (1984) Table 10-1: ultramafic-serpentine (quartz, magnesite); mafic-clay, chlorite, relict igneous minerals; calc-aluminous basic-zeolite, pumpellite, epidote, albite; pelite, semi-pelite -- clays, chlorite, sericite, quartz.

SMR050804; Smulikowski et al, 2003; Fry, 1984

very high metamorphic grade

Protolith structures almost always obliterated. Includes rocks metamorphosed in granulite (or sanidinite), and high-temperature eclogite facies. Mineral assemblages according to Fry (1984) Table 10-1: ultramafic-olivine, enstatite; mafic-hypersthene, diopside (hornblende); calc-aluminous basic-plagioclase; pelite, semi-pelite -- hypersthene + Al-minerals (K-feldspar, quartz), or sapphirine.

SMR050804; Smulikowski et al, 2003; Fry, 1984; SLTT, 2004

Medium metamorphic grade

Protolith structure typically obliterated. Includes rocks metamorphosed in high-temperature epidote-amphibolite, low-temperature amphibolite, and low temperature eclogite facies. Mineral assemblages according to Fry (1984) Table 10-1: ultramafic-olivine, talc (magnesite, anthophyllite); mafic-hornblende, (diopside, garnet); calc-aluminous basic-plagioclase; pelite, semi-pelite -- white mica, biotite, quartz (garnet, Al-minerals).

SMR050804; Smulikowski et al, 2003; Fry, 1984

Low metamorphic grade

Metamorphic effects clearly visible, protolith structures typically still observable, includes rocks metamorphosed in greenschist, high-temperature blueschist, very low temperature eclogite facies. Mineral assemblages according to Fry (1984) Table 10-1: ultramafic-serpentine (talc, magnesite); mafic-chlorite, actinolite (garnet); calc-aluminous basic-albite, epidote; pelite, semi-pelite -- white mica, chlorite, quartz, biotite (garnet, Al-minerals)..

SMR050804; Smulikowski et al, 2003; Fry, 1984

High metamorphic grade

Protolith structures almost always obliterated, evidence of partial melting common. Includes rocks metamorphosed in high-temperature amphibolite, pyroxene hornfels, and medium to high-temperature eclogite facies. Mineral assemblages according to Fry (1984) Table 10-1: ultramafic-olivine, anthophyllite, cummingtonite, enstatite; mafic-hornblende, (diopside, garnet); calc-aluminous basic-plagioclase; pelite, semi-pelite -- K-feldspar, biotite, quartz, Al-minerals (garnet), migmatite.

SMR050804; Smulikowski et al, 2003; Fry, 1984

Grain Discernibility Terms

Terms to specify degree to which individiual constituent particles are discernible in a compound material..

SMR060104

Aphanitic

Greater than 90% of rock consists of material that is too fine grained to discern individual grains with a hand lense. Operationally, the rock is too fine-grained to interpret the genesis or lithology. SLTTm2004 endorsed the The IUGS Subcommission on the Systematics of Metamorphic Rocks (SCMR) proposal to put the quantititative boundary of 'discernibility' at <0.1 mm (Schmid and others, 2002, Table 5). Such detailed grain size distinctions are impossible in the field, and very difficult under any conditions.

SMRPhaneriticAphanitic

Glassy

Grains not discernible (<1 % of rock is discernible grains), rock is glassy--no fragmental texture..

SMR060104

Phaneritic

Greater than 10% of rock consists of grains large enough to discern with hand lense. Operationally, enough of the rock is discernible to interpret the genesis or lithology.

SMRPhaneriticAphanitic

Phaneritic and aphanitic

Discernible grains are scattered in a groundmass of undiscernible grains. >20% undiscernible grains..

Simple grain size terms for particulate aggregates

Grain size terminology for specifying the modal grain size in a unimodal, moderately to very well sorted (see Particle size sorting terminology) bulk sample of grains (rock, sediment, disaggregated rock); basis for determination and confidence level are specified independently of this term. NADMSC SLTT and BGS both base terminology on size scale proposed by Wentworth, 1922; this usage is followed here..

MattiSLTTSed050604;Hallsworth&Knox, 1999, based on Wentworth, 1922; SMR050604

medium grained

Modal grain size in described particulate aggregate is between 0.25 and 2 mm; grains are mostly discernible with the unaided eye, mineralogy of many grains can be determined..

MattiSLTTSed050604; Hallsworth&Knox, 1999; Wentworth, 1922

fine grained

Modal grain size in described particulate aggregate is between 0.032 and 0.25 mm. Grains require some magnification to be discerned; only general mineralogy can be determined without microscopic inspection or other laboratory analysis..

MattiSLTTSed050604; Hallsworth&Knox, 1999; Wentworth, 1922

very fine grained

Modal grain size in described particulate aggregate is less than 0.032 mm; basically rock is too fine grained to discern particles without significant magnification..

MattiSLTTSed050604; Hallsworth&Knox, 1999; Wentworth, 1922

coarse grained

Modal grain size in described particulate aggregate is between 2 and 16 mm. Individual mineral grains are easily discernible and can be identified or at least characterized..

MattiSLTTSed050604; Hallsworth&Knox, 1999; Wentworth, 1922

cryptocrystalline

Too fine-grained for granular nature to be visible without aid of microscope.

no tracking record assigned

very coarse grained

Modal grain size in described particulate aggregate is greater than 16 mm..

Particle roundness terms

Vocabulary of terms for specifying average roundness of some collection of particles. Roundness is a measure of the sharpness of the edges between surfaces bounding a particle (see Jackson, 1997; Wadell, 1932). A grain shape term. Quantitatively defined as the average ratio of the radius of curvature grain corner (intersection of relatively straight edges) to the radius of the smallest circle that will circumscribe the grain for all corners in the silhouette of the maximum projection plane of the particle. (Pettijohn et al. 1973, p83).

SMRNGMDBImplementation123003

angular subangular subrounded
